Author: NightDream
Title: [ANN][ICO] OJOOO - Advertisement powered by Blockchain
Body: Advertising vs. Adblock https://medium.com/@ojooo/advertising-vs-adblock-b752d5e32c28  According to the newest reports, the AdBlock has been currently used by more than 200 million of users all over the world. This number has been increasing by several dozen percent per year. As estimations show, along with popularization of blocking programs, there is an increase in the global losses of advertisers and editors. The cost of blocked advertisement displays has been ca. $ 42 bln. in 2017. The advertising contents become gradually less and less visible in the network and the users perceive the aggressively advertising brands poorly.  There is only one way, to change advertising process. It’s Ojooo.  The common basis for all Ojooo services is an innovative form of advertisement — the Earn per View Online and Mobile Advertising (EPV) from Ojooo. Ojooo offers companies advertising space and user data through the Ojooo app, as well as the Ojooo portal, based on blockchain technology. It can be advertised both with the help of text advertising, as well as all common graphic advertising formats. The app collects very high-quality user data. Advertisers may gain access to this information upon user consent. This data enables advertising that is optimally adapted to the context and perfectly personalized and thus can have the maximum effect. Users can choose between an ad-free app and the display of ads. With Ojooo, potential customers can discover products faster. The peculiarity here represents the remuneration of the users for the consent of the insertion of advertisement — Earn per View and the sharing of their user data. This means that users will be rewarded with OJX tokens for displaying ads on the Ojooo portal or in the Ojooo app, as well as for sharing their own data. Ojooo treats the data collected strictly according to the Federal Data Protection Act (BDSG). Personal information is carefully separated from other data at Ojooo to avoid uniquely identifying the user.
